article.description:
Troy Hudson had 23 points, 11 assists and no
turnovers and Gary Trent came off the bench for the first time in
22 games and added 14 points as the Minnesota Timberwolves defeated
the Golden State Warriors 102-95 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Hudson posts 23 points, 11 assists for Minnesota
article.linkText: T-Wolves overcome tired legs to beat Warriors
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves shook off their weary legs and the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday night.
 
Hudson
Troy Hudson had 23 points, 11 assists and no turnovers and Gary Trent came off the bench for the first time in 22 games and added 14 points as the Timberwolves defeated the Warriors 102-95 Wednesday night. Kevin Garnett added 21 points and 14 rebounds for his league-high 29th double-double of the season. Minnesota played its second game in as many nights, arriving back in the Twin Cities at 2:30 a.m. Wednesday following a game at Houston. After shooting 36 percent in their loss to the Rockets, the Wolves improved to 50 percent Wednesday. "This was redemption for last night," Garnett said. "We weren't happy that we didn't shoot the ball well." Hudson had his best all-around game of the season despite having to play 39 minutes, one short of season-high. Backup point guard Rod Strickland missed his second consecutive game with a bruise on his right buttocks, leaving seldom-used Igor Rakocevic as his only backup. Hudson picked up his fifth foul with 6:47 remaining in the fourth quarter and the Wolves up 86-78. The Warriors scored the next seven points to pull within one on Bob Sura's tip-in with 5:13 remaining. Coach Flip Saunders had no choice but to put Hudson back in. Anthony Peeler's 3-pointer as the shot clock expired restored the Wolves' lead to four. Then, following a turnover, Garnett hit consecutive jumpers to give Minnesota a 93-86 lead. The Warriors pulled to 98-95 before Kendall Gill's long jumper with 10.9 seconds remaining iced the game. "It's easy for a team to bounce back after a poor shooting night and not shoot with confidence, but we showed professionalism and shot with a lot of confidence," Hudson said. The Wolves set the tone early, with Trent making all six of his shots in the first half to give Minnesota a 10-point lead at the break. The Wolves led by as many as 17 points late in the third quarter. The Wolves had 31 assists and only eight turnovers. "We really needed this win," Gill said. "We were tired, coming in at 2:30 off a loss, but we tried to come in and make sure our execution was better. Everything seemed to work." Jason Richardson had 32 points and Earl Boykins scored 20 for Golden State, which lost for only the second time in seven games. "The thing that's missing is consistency," Boykins said. "You have to be consistent every day and have to go out and play hard and compete. It's not a secret that we don't compete well all the time. We've just got to go out and play harder." Hudson scored seven points during a 16-5 run midway through the third quarter after Golden State had narrowed the Wolves' lead to 61-55. The Timberwolves stretched the lead to 79-62 before the Warriors came back. Game notes
The Timberwolves dressed only 10 players. Strickland had to sit out again after the bruise became infected. He had the bruise lanced and Wolves coach Flip Saunders said he would be questionable for the team's next game Friday. ... Saunders said he is ``optimistic'' that Wally Szczerbiak will play Friday. Szczerbiak has missed the past 21 games due to a dislocated left toe. Loren Woods rejoined the team Wednesday after serving a team-imposed, two-game suspension, but did not play. ... Warriors coach Eric Musselman began his career as a Timberwolves assistant in 1990, working for his late father, Bill.
